Rating: 4
I'm surprised to see how harsh some other members were of this recipe. We really enjoyed it. I made it with some variations just because I didn't have some ingredients on hand and it was great. I didn't have bell pepper so I used chopped celery which added good texture. I sauteed the white onion, celery and carrot in olive oil instead of the white wine, and omitted the chicken broth because I didn't have any on hand, which decreased the amount of liguid ingredients. I really like the addition of oats instead of bread. I replaced the tomato sauce with the same spagetti sauce I used as a topping. I baked it for about an hour so it came out moist but firm. Served it with roasted potatoes and the textures and flavors were great together. I will definitely continue to make this.

Rating: 3
Ottawa and Jersey City, please mind the language. It would be nice if Epicurious could moderate the review content. I do read the comments before making any dish but you have not exactly been constructive. This is the second time I've made this recipe. The first time it came out too sloppy as other reviewers have also noted. This time I skipped the white wine and the chicken broth, just sauteed the veggies in olive oil for 15-20 minutes. Two whole eggs in the meat mix, baked for an hour and it came out perfectly with no sogginess. Michael Smith commented in the Globe and Mail a couple of months ago that recipes should be treated as rough guidelines and not necessarily followed to the letter, this is probably a good example. I might have been a bit too heavy on the red pepper (actually I used cayenne) but I don't mind it a bit spicy. It is nice to see the occasional recipe like this on epicurious that is not heavy with fat, cream, etc. You can get good flavourful dishes with healthy fresh vegetables. Finally - I put many recipes to the three-year-old test. In this case my three-year-old son cleaned his plate so a three-fork rating is well deserved. I will definitely be making this again.

